- ## Definitions
#Definitions #SAFe #Frameworks #Scaling #Agile #Practices #Software #Product #Management 
According to the State of Agile Survey [7], the Scaled Agile Framework (SAFe) seems to be the most popular framework for scaling agile. Therefore, we decided to empirically study how SAFe has been adopted in a challenging large-scale set-up: two business lines in a highly distributed software development organization. In this paper we will help alleviate the lack of empirical studies on scaling agile by presenting the initial results of a case study on adopting SAFe.

At the program level, it defines the concept of an agile release train (ART), which is the analogy to Sprints at the team level, working at a slower time frame.

The program level contains additional roles, e.g., system team, product manager, system architect, release train engineer (RTE) and release management team.

- ## Portfolio
#Portfolio #Level #Levels #SAFe #Frameworks #Scaling #Agile #Practices #Software #Product #Management 
At the portfolio level, planning is done as epics that define large development initiatives. The optional value stream level supports the development of large and complex solutions, which require multiple, synchronized ARTs.
